        {
          "text": "Yes. I’d extract the duplicated ignore-case character comparison into a small private helper, but keep it narrowly scoped.\n\nRecommended shape:\n\n```zig\nfn ascii_eql_ignore_case(a: u8, b: u8) bool {\n    assert(std.ascii.isAlphabetic(a));\n    assert(std.ascii.isAlphabetic(b));\n\n    return std.ascii.toLower(a) == std.ascii.toLower(b);\n}\n```\n\nRationale:\n\n- The code already asserts alphabetic inputs in nearby paths, so the helper should preserve that contract.\n- It avoids repeating switch cases like `'A', 'a'` or manual lowercase comparisons.\n- It keeps case preservation intact: we only compare ignoring case, but still store the original `base` character.\n- A top-level private helper is better than a `Span` method if the comparison is used between raw input characters too, not only `Span.base`.\n\nI would not make it more general than ASCII alphabetic comparison. Vietnamese-specific logic should remain in `Span.init_diacritic_tone` and Telex rules; this helper should only answer: “are these two ASCII letters equal ignoring case?”\n\nPossible use sites:\n\n```zig\nif (ascii_eql_ignore_case(sp.base, 'a')) {\n    ...\n}\n```\n\nor:\n\n```zig\nif (ascii_eql_ignore_case(previous.base, c)) {\n    ...\n}\n```\n\nI would avoid names like `same_char` or `compare_ignore_case` because they hide the ASCII-only assumption. `ascii_eql_ignore_case` is explicit and matches Zig/std naming style.",
