          "text": "Yes, in that limited scope I would remove the asserts from `ascii_equal_ignore_case`.\n\nRecommended helper:\n\n```zig\nfn ascii_equal_ignore_case(a: u8, b: u8) bool {\n    return std.ascii.toLower(a) == std.ascii.toLower(b);\n}\n```\n\nReasoning:\n\n- `State.add` already asserts `std.ascii.isAlphabetic(c)` at entry.\n- `Span.init_diacritic_tone` already asserts alphabetic `base`, so existing `Span.base` values should also be alphabetic by construction.\n- Repeating the same precondition in the helper adds noise without strengthening the real invariant.\n- A small helper like this should not imply it owns validation if all current call sites are already within validated logic.\n\nThe tradeoff is that the helper name says `ascii`, but without asserts it will also return results for non-alphabetic ASCII bytes. That is acceptable if we treat it as a private helper with call-site preconditions.\n\nIf you want to make the contract explicit without runtime checks, add a short comment:\n\n```zig\n// Caller guarantees both bytes are ASCII alphabetic.\nfn ascii_equal_ignore_case(a: u8, b: u8) bool {\n    return std.ascii.toLower(a) == std.ascii.toLower(b);\n}\n```\n\nThat is the version I would use here.",
